> It seems to me that most people who get undergraduate CS degrees do so as 
> the first step towards a career as programmers.  It seems to me that most 
> employers who hire graduating CS majors are hiring entry-level programmers.
> 
> While you are right that at advanced graduate and doctoral levels there are 
> non-programming flavors of Computer Science, it seems to me that this 
> "icing on the cake" occurs later in the curriculum, after a solid grounding 
> in programming.  Computer Science, after all, is important because 
> computers have become quite important in our society.  And computers are 
> important because they actually run code and do things.
> 
